Data Visualization¶

Data visualization is the graphic representation of data. It involves producing images that communicate relationships among the data and is critical part of data science. We will use matplotlib and seaborn libraries for static plotting and cufflinks for interactive visualization.

Installing Libraries¶

We'll install the required libraries that we'll use in this example.

Matplotlib¶

Matplotlib is a multiplatform data visualization library built on NumPy arrays where it converts all sequences to NumPy arrays internally. Originally written as a Python alternative for MATLAB users, it is one of the most widely adopted visualization package. The biggest advantage of Matplotlib is its ability to adapt well with many operating systems and graphics backend. Matplotlib is a comprehensive library for creating publication quality plots and its the ability to customize properties make it a go to tool for data visualization.

Matplotlib has two interfaces: a) MATALB-style based interface and b) Object-oriented interface. While the former is convenient, the later approach is more powerful.

Importing Matplotlib¶

In [5]:
import matplotlib as mpl
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Set the plot style
plt.style.use('dark_background')

matplotlib.pyplot is a collection of command style functions that make matplotlib work like MATLAB. Each pyplot function makes some change to a figure. For example, it creates a figure, creates a plotting area in a figure, plots some lines in a plotting area, decorates the plot with labels, etc., Various states are preserved across function calls, so that it keeps track of things like the current figure and plotting area, and the plotting functions are directed to the current axes.

MATLAB-Style Interface¶

In [6]:
x = np.linspace(-5,5,100)
fig = plt.figure()
plt.title('Sine-Cosine Plot')
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))
plt.plot(x, np.cos(x));

In the transition between MATLAB-style functions and object-oriented methods, most plt functions translate directly to ax methods. For example, plt.plot() -> ax.plot() and plt.legend() -> ax.legend() etc., However, functions that set limits, labels and titles are slightly modified.

Refer table below for such changes.

MATLAB-style Object-oriented
plt.xlabel() ax.set_xlabel()
plt.ylabel() ax.set_ylabel()
plt.xlim() ax.set_xlim()
plt.ylim() ax.set_ylim()
plt.title() ax.set_title()

Object-oriented Interface¶

In [7]:
fig = plt.figure()
ax = plt.axes()
ax.set_title('Sine-Cosine Plot')
ax.plot(x, np.sin(x), color='blue')
ax.plot(x, np.cos(x), color='red');

Subplots¶

In [8]:
# MATLAB-style
# create a plot figure
plt.figure() 

# create the first of two panels and set current axis
plt.subplot(2, 1, 1) # (rows, columns, panel number)
plt.title('Sine')
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))

# create the second panel and set current axis
plt.subplot(2, 1, 2)
plt.title('Cosine')
plt.plot(x, np.cos(x));
In [9]:
# Object-oriented
# First create a grid of plots; ax will be an array of two Axes objects
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2)
# Call plot() method on the appropriate object
ax[0].plot(x, np.sin(x), color='blue')
ax[0].set_title('Sine')
ax[1].plot(x, np.cos(x), color='red')
ax[1].set_title('Cosine');
In [10]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2,2, figsize=(12, 10))

# Call plot() method on the appropriate object
ax[0,0].plot(x, np.sin(x), color='blue')
ax[0,0].set_title('Sine')

ax[0,1].plot(x, np.tan(x), color='green')
ax[0,1].set_title('Tangent')

ax[1,0].plot(x, np.cos(x), color='red')
ax[1,0].set_title('Cosine')

ax[1,1].plot(x, np.tanh(x), color='orange');
ax[1,1].set_ylim(-1,1)
ax[1,1].set_title('Hyberbolic Tangent');

Object-oriented approach offer high level of customization, especially for multi-plots. The above subplots can also be plotted using a for-loop.

In [11]:
# Using for loop to generate subplots
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2,2, figsize=(12,10), sharex=True)
flist = [np.sin(x), np.cos(x), np.tan(x), np.tanh(x)]
ftitle = ['Sine', 'Cosine', 'Tangent', 'Hyperbolic Tangent']
fcolor = ['blue', 'red', 'green', 'orange']

k = 0
for i in range(2):
    for j in range(2):
        ax[i,j].plot(x, flist[k], color=fcolor[k])
        ax[i,j].set_title(ftitle[k])
        k+=1

Stylesheets¶

Switch to a stylesheet by using plt.style.use('stylename'). This will change the style for the entire session. To set style temporarily (for a particular plot), we can use style context manager plt.style.context('stylename').

In [15]:
# List of available styles
plt.style.available[:6]
Out[15]:
['bmh', 'classic', 'dark_background', 'fast', 'fivethirtyeight', 'ggplot']

Style : dark_background¶

In [16]:
with plt.style.context('dark_background'):
    plt.hist(np.random.randn(100000), bins=50)
    plt.title('dark_background')

Seaborn¶

Seaborn is a Python data visualization library based on matplotlib. It provides a high-level interface for drawing attractive and informative statistical graphics. Seaborn address some of key concern of matplotlib with respected to sophisticated statistical visualization or plotting Pandas DataFrame data. While matplotlib tries to address these issue in the subsequent version, seaborn remains a natural choice.

In [22]:
import seaborn as sns
sns.set() # set the seaborn style

Overriding the matplotlib parameters¶

In [23]:
plt.plot(df)
plt.legend(df.columns, ncol=2, loc='upper left');

Heatmap¶

In [28]:
# Load the example flights dataset and convert to long-form
flights_long = sns.load_dataset("flights")
flights = flights_long.pivot("month", "year", "passengers")

# Draw a heatmap with the numeric values in each cell
f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(9, 6))
sns.heatmap(flights, annot=True, fmt="d", linewidths=.5, ax=ax)
ax.set_title('Heat Map');
